0.body: This is the documentation for the wireless networking setup at Farmhill Learning Community . The wireless network is setup using a router running OpenWrt , an open-source operating system for wireless routers based on linux. Apart for providing wireless network, this setup also provides additional services like hosting static websites and services to sync content from various devices in the local network.
0.breadcrumbs: Wireless Networking Setup for Farmhill Learning » Wireless Networking Setup for Farmhill Learning
0.title: Wireless Networking Setup for Farmhill Learning

1.body: The current setup uses D-Link DIR-853 A3 wireless router.
1.title: The Router

10.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Securing the Device » Connecting to an existing wifi network
10.title: Connecting to an existing wifi network

11.body: Configure the router to connect to an existing wifi network to reach the internet.
11.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Connecting to client Wi-Fi network
11.title: Connecting to client Wi-Fi network

12.body: Go to Network > Wireless page in the router admin interface. Click on the Scan button of radio0. The radio0 is the 2.4 GHz network and the radio1 is the 5 GHz network. Use radio1 instead of radio0 if you would like to connect to a 5 GHznetwork.
12.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Step 1: Go to Wireless Overview page
12.title: Step 1: Go to Wireless Overview page

13.body: You'll see the Wireless Scan dialog. Select the network that you want to join.
13.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Step 2: Wireles Scan
13.title: Step 2: Wireles Scan

14.body: You'll be prompted with the Joining Network dialog. Please enter the wifi password in the WPA passphase field and Submit . Click Save on the next dialog.
14.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Step 3: Join Network
14.title: Step 3: Join Network

15.body: You'll be back to the Wireless Overview page. Click on Save and Apply at the bottom of the page. The router will apply the changes and restart. And you'll see an entry in the Associated Stations section.
15.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Step 4: Save & Apply
15.title: Step 4: Save & Apply

16.body: You should be able to connect to internet from your laptop. Verify by opening any website from your browser or by running ping google.com from terminal. The router is connected to internet and can be used with an ethernet connection, but the wifi access point is not enabled yet. We'll configure that in the next step.
16.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to Client Wi-Fi Network » Step 5: Verify
16.title: Step 5: Verify

17.body: Enable wifi access points in the router so that devices in the visinity (laptops and mobile phones) can connect to the router. The router has two accesspoints one each for 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz band. The 2.4 GHz band has lower bandwidth, but spans longer distances. The 5 GHz band on the other hand has high bandwidth, but covers only a short distance.
17.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Enable Wi-Fi Access Point » Enable Wifi Access Point
17.title: Enable Wifi Access Point

18.body: Click on the Edit button of the first access point (second row). Set the access point name. Go to the Wireless Security tab, select WPA2-PSK (strong security) as Encryption and set a password in the Key field. Click on the Save button. Once you are back on the wireless overview page, click on the Enable button for the access point. The 2.GHz access point is now live.
18.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Enable Wi-Fi Access Point » Configure 2.4 GHz Access Point
18.title: Configure 2.4 GHz Access Point

19.body: Click on the Edit button of the second access point (last row). Repeat the same steps as in the previous step. Don't forget to enable to access point at the end. You can select the same name for both the access points if you want the connecting device to automatically select best of these network, or you can have separate names. The possible names would be Farmhill Wifi and Farmhill Wifi 5G for 2.4 and 5 GHz respectively.
19.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Enable Wi-Fi Access Point » Configure 5 GHz Access Point
19.title: Configure 5 GHz Access Point

2.body: Model: DIR-853 H/W Ver: A3 CPU: MIPS 1004Kc V2.15 880MHz (2 cores, 4 threads) RAM: 256 MB Disk: 24 MB This device has resonably good compute and memory, but not enough disk space to install many external software. Using external USD disk will address that issue.
2.title: The Specs

20.body: Now both the access points are live. You can verify by connecting to wifi from a laptop or a mobile phone.
20.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Enable Wi-Fi Access Point » Verifying
20.title: Verifying

3.body: To setup the router, we need to the following three things. Installing OpenWRT firmware Connecting to the router from a laptop Secure the device Connecting to wifi network Enable wifi access points
3.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Setting up the Router
3.title: Setting up the Router

4.body: Please note that this needs to be done only once. The router may have this firmware already installed. The OpenWRT Firmware can be downloaded using the firmware-selector of openwrt . You need to download the factory image. The Latest version as of Feb 2025 is linked below. OpenWrt firmware version 24.10 for model D-Link DIR-853 A3 . Every router will have a way to update firmware. It is available from the admin interface of the router, typically in the System tab/menu and it will be labelled as Backup / update firmware . Once you select the factory image and upload, the led lights on router will flash repeated indicating that it is resetting and after a minute or so, the router will be ready with openwrt.
4.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Installing OpenWrt Firmware » Installing OpenWRT Firmware
4.title: Installing OpenWRT Firmware

5.body: Connect your laptop to the router using ethernet cable to configure it. You can configure the router by connecting it to a laptop via ethernet. Connect the laptop ethernet port to one of the LAN ports (one of the yellow ports).
5.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to the Router » Connecting to the Router
5.title: Connecting to the Router

6.body:
After connecting, setup the laptop with manual IP address with the following settings. IP Address: 192.168.1.2
Subnet mark: 255.255.255.0
Gateway: 192.168.1.1
6.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to the Router » Network Setup
6.title: Network Setup

7.body:
After the settings are done, you can verify if you can reach the router by running the ping command from terminal/command promt. $ ping 192.168.1.1

^C

rtt min/avg/max/mdev = 0.675/0.679/0.682/0.003 ms
7.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to the Router » Ping Test
7.title: Ping Test

8.body: Open your browser and visit http://192.168.1.1/ or http://openwrt.lan . It will ask you to login. Press Log in without entering any password. You'll be see the status page of the router. Congratulations! You have sucessfully connected to the router. The next step is to secure the device.
8.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Connecting to the Router » The Router Admin Interface
8.title: The Router Admin Interface

9.body: Set a password to secure the router from unauthrized access. When you go to the router web interface, it was a "No password set!" warning at the top of the page. Click on Go to password configuration and set a password.
9.breadcrumbs: Setting up the Router » Securing the Device » Securing the Device
9.title: Securing the Device
